{"title_page": "Gallbladder flush", "text_new": "{{more medical citations needed|date=May 2018}}\nThe '''gallbladder flush''' or '''liver cleanse''' is an [[alternative medicine]] practice involving fasting, followed by the ingestion of some combination of [[magnesium sulfate|Epsom salt]], [[olive oil]], and [[grapefruit]] juice, in some cases substituted by other, similar ingredients.<ref name=AMR/> Those who advocate it claim that it is possible to remove not only the well-known [[gallstone]]s from the [[gallbladder]], but also the so-called intra-hepatic stones from the [[bile duct]]s of the [[liver]] by this procedure.\n\nThere are different sets of rules, according to which a gallbladder flush is performed. One can distinguish between \"recipes\" originating in traditional folk medicine<ref>P. C. Royal, ''Herbally Yours. A comprehensive herbal handbook simple enough for the herbal student, complete enough for the herbal practitioner,'' Hurricane (Utah) <sup>3</sup>1982, 117f.</ref> and those of which the author is known.\n\nWhen scientifically analyzed, the \"gallstones\" produced by a group of patients were found to contain no cholesterol, bilirubin, or calcium, which characterizes the makeup of gallstones, but instead were 75% fatty acids.<ref name=AMR>{{cite journal|last1=Gaby|first1=Alan, R.|title=Nutritional Approaches to Prevention and Treatment of Gallstones|journal=Alternative Medicine Review |pmid=19803550|volume=14|year=2009|pages=258\u201367}}</ref> In two cases, chemical analysis of supposed gallstones that were excreted in the course of a gallbladder flush showed that these were not real gallstones, but \"soap stones\", which are structures formed in the [[gastrointestinal tract|gut]] due to a reaction of the digestive juices with the ingested treatment.<ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 15836886 | doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(05)66373-8 | volume=365 | title=Could these be gallstones? | year=2005 | journal=Lancet | page=1388 | last1 = Sies | first1 = CW | last2 = Brooker | first2 = J}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | pmid = 19718602 | doi=10.1055/s-0029-1234016 | volume=134 | title=[Flushing stones? \"Liver purging\" and \"gallbladder lavage\"] | year=2009 | journal=Dtsch Med Wochenschr | page=1774 | last1 = Ewald | first1 = N | last2 = Hardt | first2 = PD | lang = de }}</ref>\n\n== Risks ==\nPeople attempting this treatment often experience abdominal pain and diarrhea.<ref name=AMR/>\n\nIn one reported case, a patient suffered a biliary [[pancreatitis]] after performing a gallbladder flush.<ref>S. U. Christl, ''Bili\u00e4re Pankreatitis nach alternativmedizinischer Leberreinigung'', Die Medizinische Welt  2006; 57 12:596-598. (article in German)</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n[[Category:Biologically-based therapies]]\n[[Category:Herbalism]]\n[[Category:Gallbladder]]\n", "text_old": "{{medref|date=May 2018}}\nThe '''gallbladder flush''' or '''liver cleanse''' is an [[alternative medicine]] practice involving fasting, followed by the ingestion of some combination of [[magnesium sulfate|Epsom salt]], [[olive oil]], and [[grapefruit]] juice, in some cases substituted by other, similar ingredients.<ref name=AMR/> Those who advocate it claim that it is possible to remove not only the well-known [[gallstone]]s from the [[gallbladder]], but also the so-called intra-hepatic stones from the [[bile duct]]s of the [[liver]] by this procedure.\n\nThere are different sets of rules, according to which a gallbladder flush is performed. One can distinguish between \"recipes\" originating in traditional folk medicine<ref>P. C. Royal, ''Herbally Yours. A comprehensive herbal handbook simple enough for the herbal student, complete enough for the herbal practitioner,'' Hurricane (Utah) <sup>3</sup>1982, 117f.</ref> and those of which the author is known.\n\nWhen scientifically analyzed, the \"gallstones\" produced by a group of patients were found to contain no cholesterol, bilirubin, or calcium, which characterizes the makeup of gallstones, but instead were 75% fatty acids.<ref name=AMR>{{cite journal|last1=Gaby|first1=Alan, R.|title=Nutritional Approaches to Prevention and Treatment of Gallstones|journal=Alternative Medicine Review |pmid=19803550}}</ref> In two cases, chemical analysis of supposed gallstones that were excreted in the course of a gallbladder flush showed that these were not real gallstones, but \"soap stones\", which are structures formed in the [[gastrointestinal tract|gut]] due to a reaction of the digestive juices with the ingested treatment.<ref>C. W. Sies, J. Brooker, ''Could these be gallstones?,'' The Lancet, Volume 365, Issue 9468, page 1388, 16 April 2005.  {{PMID|15836886}}</ref><ref>N. Ewald, P. Hardt, ''Flushing Stones? \u201eLeberreinigung\u201c und \u201eGallensp\u00fclungen\u201c,'' DMW, Volume 134 (36), 2009, page 1774. (article in German) {{PMID|19718602}}</ref>\n\n== Risks ==\nPeople attempting this treatment often experience abdominal pain and diarrhea.<ref name=AMR/>\n\nIn one reported case, a patient suffered a biliary [[pancreatitis]] after performing a gallbladder flush.<ref>S. U. Christl, ''Bili\u00e4re Pankreatitis nach alternativmedizinischer Leberreinigung'', Die Medizinische Welt  2006; 57 12:596-598. (article in German)</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references/>\n\n[[Category:Biologically-based therapies]]\n[[Category:Herbalism]]\n[[Category:Gallbladder]]\n", "name_user": "Rjwilmsi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Journal cites:,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gallbladder_flush"}
